#compdef cherrybomb
# =============================================================================
# cherrybomb — BLST Security's "CLI tool that helps you avoid
#              undefined user behavior by auditing your API
#              specifications, validating them and running API
#              security tests" — a Rust CLI for OpenAPI / Swagger
#              specification security analysis.  Parses OAS
#              (OpenAPI Specification) v3 documents, validates
#              their schema for completeness + correctness, and
#              runs a battery of security checks identifying
#              endpoints lacking auth, missing rate limits,
#              undefined response codes, sensitive-data
#              exposure, and other API security anti-patterns.
#              Distinguishing from Postman, Insomnia, openapi-
#              cli, ZAP API addon, and other API tools by:
#                - DEFENSIVE-SECURITY FOCUS — cherrybomb's
#                  primary job is to AUDIT your own OpenAPI
#                  specs for security gaps before deployment:
#                  flagging unauthenticated endpoints, missing
#                  CORS / security headers, response schemas
#                  that may leak PII, endpoints without rate
#                  limit definitions, etc.  Use case is API
#                  hardening for production deployments
#                  (authorized testing on your own APIs).
#                - OAS v3 SCHEMA VALIDATION — parses the
#                  OpenAPI v3 schema rigorously; flags
#                  malformed schemas (missing required fields,
#                  type-mismatched examples, invalid $refs,
#                  duplicate operationIds)
#                - PROFILE-BASED RULE SETS via -p PROFILE —
#                  preset rule collections for common audit
#                  scenarios: API design quality, security
#                  audit, PII compliance, etc.
#                - AUTHENTICATION MODES via `auth` subcommand
#                  — define HTTP / API Key / OAuth2 / Bearer
#                  auth so cherrybomb can probe authenticated
#                  endpoints during testing
#                - COMFY-TABLE OUTPUT — terminal-friendly
#                  result tables with color highlighting
#                  (--no-color to disable)
#                - JSON OUTPUT via --format Json — machine-
#                  parseable results for CI integration
#                - CONFIG FILE via -c FILE — YAML (.yaml) or
#                  JSON (.json) configuration; merges with
#                  command-line options at runtime
#                - SERVER OVERRIDE via --server URL — replace
#                  the OAS document's `servers` array with a
#                  specific URL (useful for testing against
#                  staging environments)
#                - TLS HANDLING via -i/--ignore-tls-errors —
#                  skip TLS validation for testing internal
#                  environments with self-signed certs
#                - TELEMETRY OPT-OUT via --no-telemetry —
#                  prevents the binary from sending anonymous
#                  usage stats to BLST Security's servers
#                - rustls TLS — pure-Rust TLS via reqwest
#                  with rustls-tls feature (no OpenSSL
#                  dependency)
#                - ASCII-ART BANNER — playful "Cherrybomb"
#                  banner printed at startup (suppress with
#                  --quiet)
#                - WORKSPACE STRUCTURE — cherrybomb-engine
#                  (core engine), cherrybomb-oas (OAS schema
#                  library), cherrybomb (CLI wrapper)
#              Used by: API security teams hardening their own
#              OpenAPI deployments, DevSecOps pipelines auditing
#              spec quality before deployment, and as a
#              reference implementation of serde_yaml + serde
#              + clap derive + tokio + reqwest + rustls +
#              comfy-table composition in Rust for defensive
#              security tooling.
#
# Author:  BLST Security (blstsecurity.com) — Israeli API
#          security firm.  cherrybomb maintained by BLST's
#          engineering team.  Released ~2022; current version
#          1.0.1.  License: Apache-2.0.
# Source:  https://github.com/blst-security/cherrybomb
#          https://github.com/blst-security/cherrybomb/blob/main/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/blst-security/cherrybomb/blob/main/src/options.rs
#          https://github.com/blst-security/cherrybomb/blob/main/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     src/options.rs — uses clap v4 derive (well-documented
#          elsewhere).  Headline library: **serde_yaml** (clap
#          is documented across hundreds of Rust completions;
#          serde_yaml is the new variant being documented here,
#          opening Axis 20 — YAML Parsing).
# Library: serde_yaml (https://github.com/dtolnay/serde-yaml —
#          "Strongly typed YAML library for Rust" — David
#          Tolnay (dtolnay on GitHub).  Distinct from all
#          previously-documented Rust libraries by being:
#             1. SERDE INTEGRATION — serde_yaml is a serde
#                serializer + deserializer for YAML.  The
#                same #[derive(Serialize, Deserialize)] structs
#                used for JSON / TOML / MessagePack / RON work
#                with YAML:
#                  use serde::{Serialize, Deserialize};
#                  use serde_yaml;
#                  #[derive(Serialize, Deserialize)]
#                  struct Config {
#                      name: String,
#                      version: String,
#                      dependencies: Vec<String>,
#                  }
#                  let yaml = "name: my-app\nversion: '1.0'\ndependencies:\n  - tokio\n  - serde";
#                  let cfg: Config = serde_yaml::from_str(yaml)?;
#                  let yaml_out = serde_yaml::to_string(&cfg)?;
#                Distinct from yaml-rust (raw YAML, no serde)
#                and yaml-cpp-style libraries.
#             2. YAML 1.2 + 1.1 SUPPORT — supports the YAML
#                1.2 specification (current standard) while
#                accepting most YAML 1.1 documents.  Distinct
#                from older YAML libraries that target only
#                1.1.
#             3. DOCUMENT-STREAM SUPPORT — multiple YAML
#                documents in a single file separated by `---`
#                are parsed as a stream:
#                  let docs: Vec<Value> = serde_yaml::Deserializer::from_str(input)
#                      .map(|d| Value::deserialize(d))
#                      .collect::<Result<_, _>>()?;
#                Useful for Kubernetes manifests (which often
#                contain multiple resources per file).
#             4. SERDE_YAML::VALUE — untyped YAML access via
#                an enum (Null / Bool / Number / String /
#                Sequence / Mapping / Tagged); useful for
#                schema-less YAML (configuration files,
#                schema-flexible parsing):
#                  let value: serde_yaml::Value = serde_yaml::from_str(yaml)?;
#                  if let Some(name) = value.get("name").and_then(|v| v.as_str()) {
#                      println!("Name: {}", name);
#                  }
#             5. TYPED ALIAS PRESERVATION — YAML anchors + aliases
#                (`&anchor` / `*alias`) preserved during parsing
#                + serialization, enabling YAML files with
#                shared subtrees:
#                  defaults: &defaults
#                    timeout: 30
#                    retries: 3
#                  endpoint1:
#                    <<: *defaults
#                    url: https://api.example.com
#                  endpoint2:
#                    <<: *defaults
#                    url: https://api.example.org
#             6. PRETTY-PRINT via serde_yaml::to_writer / to_string
#                — formatted output with consistent indentation
#                + standard quoting rules
#             7. ZERO COPY where possible — borrows from input
#                lifetime when the parsed value contains string
#                slices
#             8. RETIRED IN MARCH 2024 — David Tolnay archived
#                serde_yaml on March 25, 2024 citing maintenance
#                burden and YAML's design complexity.  Crate
#                remains downloadable; existing users continue
#                using it.  Community successors include
#                serde-yml (sebastien-rousseau/serde-yml), serde-
#                yaml-bw (Daniel Lockard's backward-compatible
#                fork), saphyr (kazo0/saphyr).  However,
#                serde_yaml remains the de facto standard for
#                Rust YAML even post-retirement due to
#                installed-base inertia.  cherrybomb (THIS),
#                kube-rs, helm-rs, many cargo subcommands,
#                etc. still depend on serde_yaml 0.9.x.
#             9. DAVID-TOLNAY ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — David
#                Tolnay (dtolnay on GitHub) is among the most
#                prolific Rust crate maintainers:
#                  * serde         — serialization framework
#                                     (THE Rust serde framework)
#                  * serde_json    — JSON serde implementation
#                  * serde_yaml    — YAML serde implementation
#                                     (THIS, retired 2024)
#                  * thiserror     — error-trait derive
#                  * anyhow        — concrete error type
#                  * proc-macro2   — Rust procedural macros
#                  * quote         — quasi-quote macro
#                  * syn           — Rust syntax parser
#                  * inventory     — typed runtime registry
#                  * paste         — identifier pasting macro
#                  * dyn-clone     — clone trait objects
#                  * link-cplusplus — C++ linking helper
#                  * countless others (50+ widely-used Rust crates)
#                Tolnay-maintained crates underpin the entire
#                Rust serde ecosystem; serde alone is the most
#                downloaded Rust crate.
#            10. RUST YAML CANONICAL CHOICE — for the Rust
#                ecosystem's decade-long history, "use
#                serde_yaml" has been the canonical answer to
#                "how do I parse YAML in Rust" — even after
#                its 2024 retirement.  The successor crates
#                (serde-yml, serde-yaml-bw, saphyr) are still
#                gaining adoption; serde_yaml's installed-base
#                dominance persists in 2026.)
# License: MIT OR Apache-2.0 (serde_yaml); Apache-2.0 (cherrybomb)
# Status:  serde_yaml — 1,019+ stars on dtolnay/serde-yaml,
#          ~250M crates.io downloads (TOP-30 Rust crate by
#          downloads); foundational YAML library used by:
#            * kube-rs (Rust Kubernetes client; YAML manifests)
#            * cargo (Cargo.lock + some metadata)
#            * cargo-generate (template config)
#            * cargo-edit (some YAML configs)
#            * helm-rs (Helm in Rust)
#            * rust-analyzer (some configs)
#            * sccache (config)
#            * kubernetes-related Rust tools
#            * cherrybomb (THIS — OpenAPI YAML)
#            * 10,000+ Rust applications
#          cherrybomb — 1,229+ stars on blst-security/cherrybomb;
#          used by DevSecOps + API security teams.
